The actual Long March
Every nation has its founding myth.
For communist China, it is the Long March – a story that parallels the Exodus of the Israelites led by Moses from Egypt.
The sentence "Ich bin damit aufgewachsen." translates to "I grew up with it." in English.
The myth is quickly told.
The young Communist Party and its three Red Armies were driven out of their southern bases by Chiang Kai-shek's nationalist government at the beginning of the 1930s.
Chased and tormented by their enemies, they crossed high mountains, raging rivers, and rugged pastures, with Mao steering the march from victory to victory.
After two years and 16,000 kilometers of steadfastness, courage, and hope, despite incredibly poor prospects, the Red Armies reached Northwest China.
Only one-fifth of the 200,000 soldiers remained - exhausted, badly wounded, but full of defiance.
Ten years later, they struck back, defeated Chiang Kai-shek, and founded Mao's New China.
To what extent does China's founding myth hold up to reality?
In the year 2004, seventy years after the beginning of the Long March, I set out to follow its trail.
It is still a frightening journey through regions that have changed little to this day, inaccessible and incredibly poor.
Of the 40,000 survivors, perhaps only about 500 are still alive today. I found contact with 40 of them and spoke to them – they were ordinary people who were left behind or managed to survive until the end, but their stories were extremely enlightening.
Huán Zhìjī was still a child, barely taller than his rifle, when he joined the Red Army.
He had no choice: his father had been arrested and was not released until Huang agreed.
He thought of desertion, but stayed nonetheless, out of fear of being caught and shot.
Many ran away.
Six weeks into the march, Mao's First Army had shrunk from 86,000 to 30,000 soldiers.
The blame for this loss is still attributed to the Battle of the Xiang River, which was the first major engagement of the army on its march.
But no more than 15,000 died in the battle, the rest disappeared.
Another battle, fought at the Dadu River, is at the center of the legend of the Long March. Allegedly, 22 brave men overwhelmed a regiment of nationalist troops that guarded the chains of the Luding Bridge with machine guns, clearing the way for the marchers.
Mao told Edgar Snow, the author of Red Star Over China, that crossing the Dadu River was the most significant event on the Long March, and it is therefore praised as such today.
However, documents that I have reviewed suggest that the general who commanded the division over the Dadu River initially told party historians a completely different story. "The situation wasn't as complicated as people portrayed it later," he said. "When examining historical facts, one should pay attention to the truth."
"How they are portrayed is another matter."
So the legend lives on.
Above Dadu, there was merely a trivial argument.
The local warlord, who hated Chiang Kai-shek, let Mao pass.
As a reward, he later received a ministerial position in the communist government.
The march participants did not know where they were going.
There were constant discussions about the final goal.
When they met in North China in October 1936, this was celebrated as the end of the march.
But the "promised land" was not as promised.
It could barely feed its own population, let alone the Red Army.
The soldiers had no clothing to protect themselves from the icy cold.
The women were ordered to turn around and go back home because there was not enough food.
Just a month after the merger of the three Red Armies, the party decided that the Long March must continue.
But she saved Chiang Kai-shek's kidnapping by the general whom Chiang had appointed to destroy the Communists.
As part of the price for his release, Chiang acknowledged the Communists as the legitimate government.
The Long March was concluded.
Not for the 21,000 men and women of the Western Legion, however.
They belonged to the Fourth Army, which was led by Zhang Guotao, Mao's main rival, and their mission was to obtain aid from Russia across the western Chinese border.
But Mao gave them contradictory orders, so that they could neither fight nor retreat.
Trapped on barren land where survival was difficult, they were eradicated by the superior forces of the Muslim warlords.
Only 400 reached the border, while the rest were killed or captured.
It was the greatest defeat of the Red Army.
Nevertheless, she is absent from the official historical narrative.
A Muslim commander took Lieutenant Wang Quanyan as his mistress.
This was sufficient to make her appear a traitor in the eyes of the party and to deny all those years she had devoted to the army.
She and the other survivors of the Fourth Army had to fight for nearly half a century to be recognized as participants in the march.
The participants of the Long March were resolute, fought, starved, despairing at times, and persevered.
The hunger made the soldiers take hostages to extort ransom money.
The liquidations continued until practically no officers were left to take command in the battles.
If the marchers had doubts, they overcame them with the help of communist propaganda.
They bore their martyrdom with a courage and self-sacrifice that is unmatched in the history of China and other nations.
Sure, please provide the German sentence that you would like me to translate into English.
What drove her to do that?
I questioned one of the top generals about what he knew about communism back then. "I didn't know any more then than I do now," he replied. "I even doubt that Mao himself really understood what it was." For him, who had survived extreme poverty and oppression, communism was a beautiful dream that kept him alive, a hope for a just and progressive society.
No one may have known - or been able to know - how much suffering was yet to come, how great the sacrifice would be, and how enormous the difference between dream and reality would be.
